rComments: Took this class over the summer and it wasn't to bad at all. She is always willing to help if you have questions and the material is pretty straight forward. Focus on what she covers in class and spends the most time on

Professor Williams is a GREAT professor. Her tests are fair & you WILL HAVE TO study everything she lectures. She really cares about passing her students. Her grading is not like most professors & not your entire grade will be based on exams. 10% of your grade is usually based on HW/Short papers. She is Friendly & Wonderful! :)

Honestly, one of the worst Biology Professors I have taken at UCSC. Doesnt answer questions, confuses students, always tells us to know the jisp of the main concept, but expects you to know the concept in fine detail. Very unorganized TEST are the WORST she adds in concepts that she spent a whole 1 second on if even that. Honestly the WORST at UCSC

I personally felt that Susan Williams wasn't that bad of a professor. All of the material she lectured from were straight out of the textbook. Though there was a lot of material, the entire course was straight forward. If you keep up with the material and study hard through the textbook you should get a good grade.

Professor was very unorganized and rushed lectures cramming in chapter after chapter with no clarity of what we were expected to know. Grades were never updated until posted on my ucsc. I wrote her an email the day grades were posted and have yet to get a response. Very poor teaching techniques, even the TAs were lost.

Her lectures were identical to the book readings, her exams were extremely poorly written with grammar errors and terrible wording. I called her out on a bad exam question and she said she would throw that q out. She also messed up some scantron scores because the machine was faulty. How the heck the does that happen?

Uses 20+ slides per class, which are pieces taken from the textbook, and speeds through them. Puts emphasis on the "big picture" and then tests on little details. READ THE BACK OF THE BOOK QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS (giveaway questions on exams) Go to section, your TA is your only hope unless you enjoy reading all 40 chapters WITH SPECIFIC DETAIL.

Her lectures are fast and complicated but stick to the book for easy review. You need to keep up, and it's not easy, but she's willing to help. This class requires more engagement than most students are willing to give but that's not a bad thing; this professor just isn't for slackers.

She read off PowerPoint slides that are exactly in the book. Also, she rush through so many chapters in a week. Our first midterm was multiple choice- about 6 chapters & first 2week of class. Then, second midterm was about 15 to 20 chapters (the week after thanksgiving), and final exam was again 6-7 chapters. Her exams were multiple choice.

The lectures were her essentially reading the powerpoints but mispronouncing all of the words and making the concepts more difficult to understand. Class was also really disorganized and the students were never told what they were expected to know. However, her tests were really easy.

This professor basically just reads from the text book. She moved extremely fast through the lecture slides and confuses majority of the students in lecture. Most of the students that attend lecture are daydreaming or on their laptops. To be honest I found biochem interesting before her class, but now this is not the case.

I really do not like her teaching style of just taking captions from the book and reading them off to us quickly. Goes through about 20-30 slides s lecture and goes very quickly. Her tests are a bit tricky and most students seemed to either be not paying attention or just blankly staring off into space. Not my favorite teacher.
